An important difference  between inflation driven by a  spinor and the
conventional  scenarios is the  reheating mechanism  after the  end of
inflation.  In  the conventional  scenarios, the universe  is reheated
when  the scalar  field starts  oscillating around  the bottom  of its
potential and decays into particles.
If   inflation   is  driven   by   a   spinor   field,  the   quantity
  evolves  according  to Eq.  ()  and
hence does not oscillate.   Nevertheless, there are several mechanisms
to  reheat  the  universe.   One  of them  is  gravitational  particle
production at  the end of inflation ; more
efficient ways have been suggested in.

 
